                <title type="mainTitle" xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Nāgārjunagarbha</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="bo">འཕགས་པ་ཀླུ་སྒྲུབ་སྙིང་པོ།</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">'phags pa klu sgrub snying po</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="bo">སློབ་དཔོན་ཆེན་པོ་ཀླུ་སྒྲུབ་སྙིང་པོ།</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">slob dpon chen po klu sgrub snying po</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="bo">སློབ་དཔོན་འཕགས་པ་ཀླུ་སྒྲུབ་སྙིང་པོ།</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">slob dpon 'phags pa klu sgrub snying po</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="bo">སློབ་དཔོན་ཀླུ་སྒྲུབ་སྙིང་པོའི་ཞལ་སྔ་ནས།</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">slob dpon klu sgrub snying po'i zhal snga nas</title>
                <title type="otherTitle" xml:lang="en">Dudjom and Kapstein (The Nyingma School of Tibetan Buddhism, vol. 1, p. 479) note that the balimācārya [master of offerings] at Vikramaśīla was named Nāgārjunagarbha but is never called "ārya" ('phags pa). However, sometimes ārya Nāgārjuna is referred to as ārya Nāgārjunagarbha, and so references by that name should not be confused with the master of offerings at Vikramaśīla. There is a similar question of authorship with regard to the Caturmudrānvaya (Toh. 2225) attributed to a Nāgārjunagarbhapādā (klu sgrub snying po zhal snga nas) that is subsequently quoted by Advayavajra in the Pañcatathāgatamudrāvivaraṇa (Toh. 2242).</title>
